<h2 id="___sec8">Basic Syllabus </h2>

<p>
The syllabus for this course consists of the lecture notes on the webpage (chapter 11-16) and 3 compulsory projects. The projects will be graded and count 1/3 each of the final mark. 

<ul>
 <li> Monte Carlo methods in physics (<a href="https://github.com/CompPhysics/ComputationalPhysics2/tree/master/doc/Lectures" target="_self">Lecture notes chapters 11-16</a>)</li>
</ul>

A good text that can be used (with more math plus much material on parallelization) is <a href="http://www.cambridge.org/us/academic/subjects/computer-science/scientific-computing-scientific-software/parallel-scientific-computing-c-and-mpi-seamless-approach-parallel-algorithms-and-their-implementation" target="_self">Parallel Scientific Computing in C++ and MPI, of Karniadakis and Kirby III</a>.

<h2 id="___sec9">Additional literature </h2>
<div class="alert alert-block alert-block alert-text-normal">
<b></b>
<p>
In addition we recommend highly the texts on Numerical Recipes in C++ or Fortran90 by Press et al. The C, F77 and
Fortran90 can be downloaded down for free, follow the links at <a href="http://www.nr.com/" target="_self">Numerical Recipes</a>.

<p>
The program library in C++ and Fortran2008 used in this course is a rewritten version of the Numerical Recipes codes.
</div>


<p>
